We are unable to sponsor H1b visas currently"  Role: Senior Frontend Web Developer Location: Oakland, CA Duration: Contract  Job Description:  Description: The Senior Front-End Web Developer is responsible for providing advanced level contribution in the analysis, design, development, and implementation of a modernized and accessible Treasurer- Tax Collector’s property tax portal. We are building on Java-based headless CMS, Magnolia, integrated with Astro Framework and Storybook and integrating with back-office property tax systems to provide services to our county constituents.  Knowledge and Skills: Frontend technologies & architecture in large-scale applications using web components. Working with content management systems (CMS). Working with headless CMS preferred (example: AEM, Magnolia, or similar). Experience with JAM stack architecture. Working with git-based mono repo codebase. Deploying code and understanding infrastructure (CI/CD pipelines). JavaScript expertise to build decoupled, testable, and maintainable frontends. Cloud Architecture in Azure or AWS (cloud-native technologies), containers, Docker, Kubernetes, and PostgreSQL is a plus. Web application development using RESTful services. Having worked on or with a design system. Automated unit testing - frameworks like Jest, vitest, etc. Scaling front-end engineering through component-driven development - delivering reusable modules and efficient web applications.  Thanks Vani Perumandla vani@triuneinfomatics.com 510-426-8608

CONVERSATION TITLE: Opening for Frontend/React Developer- SF- Contract
SUBJECT: Opening for Frontend/React Developer- SF- Contract
CONTENT: Hi Ashita.  I just attempted the React test you sent me.   You failed to mention that it was going to capture my audio, video, & desktop environment. I think this is something you should review with your candidates moving forward. There are some serious privacy concerns here.  Also this test didn't actually test my knowledge of working with React, since I was not able to use the tools I normally would in engineering. I rely on these tools to navigate the code base, and then test the data coming in from the backend to render the data on the frontend.   Where was the data coming from for the todo list? How was I supposed to find that? Was I expected to navigate the file structure of the server to find the data?  I'm not sure what this test was supposed to uncover about my ability to engineer, but I didn't move forward with this test. Also, you should consider a coding platform that supports ES6 Javascript standards, since that's what most engineers use now.

CONVERSATION TITLE: Remote Opportunity
SUBJECT: Remote Opportunity
CONTENT: Hello: I came across your profile and I wanted to see if you could be interested in this full-time/remote opportunity? Please let me know. Thanks! Eric  We’re looking for a senior full stack developer to lead our development team. You can either be the type of person who obsesses about the front-end work, or obsesses about the backend, so long as, when necessary, you can dive into the other side of the pool.  Day to day, we build lots of features for our existing services, we update and improve our services to incorporate user requests, and we ensure compliance and quality across our client users. You’ll be the lead building most of features, will be the lead in managing the stack, and can help choose your Junior Full Stack dev.  This is a position for people who love to focus on making one or two things, and who focus on doing those things exceptionally well. We need people that are to be delivery, service, and execution focused, and who are committed to growing their aptitude over time. Our clients work in a variety of time zones and your ready availability is essential.  Really, the ‘ideal” candidate only needs a handful of skills:  HTML SASS / CSS JavaScript Vue.js or React Python Django Docker Google Cloud Platform  Eric Dollin Senior Recruiting Executive at Oxford Global Resources

CONVERSATION TITLE: Jason I'd Love To Chat- MarketNation (Next Gen eCommerce Build)- Ex eBay/Amazon/Walmart Execs Team Up- 100% Remote- Sr Software Engineer (Vue/Node)- Part Time Till Series A- Unique Situation
SUBJECT: Jason I'd Love To Chat- MarketNation (Next Gen eCommerce Build)- Ex eBay/Amazon/Walmart Execs Team Up- 100% Remote- Sr Software Engineer (Vue/Node)- Part Time Till Series A- Unique Situation
CONTENT: Hi Jason,  I had a great chat yesterday afternoon with the CTO (ex PayPal Architect) and CEO (Ex eBay Exec) of MarketNation.  We were introduced to them from some executives at eBay whom we have known for many years.  MarketNation came into existence in 2019 to help Brands and their Distribution Partners verticalize their operations by making sales direct-to-consumer easy and everywhere.  Basically, putting the power back into the hands of companies directly in terms of connecting them to consumers directly versus using Amazon as an example.  The product focus has a real anti amazon vibe in some sense, but in a positive/needed way industry wise.  They have 6 high level investors from Walmart already prepared for their series A.  Their team/board is made up of ex Amazon, eBay and Walmart eCommerce leaders with 100+ years of marketplace expertise.  I got vibe they are on to something substantial to say the least.  They have been using an dev agency in the East Coast, but now gearing up to build an in-house team.  They are in need of a Sr Software Engineer ideally with some e-commerce experience mixed with Vuejs and Nodejs.  Their CTO was a key Architect from PayPal for 6+ years and he is the one you would work closely with as they scale.  Given they are pre series A they are hoping to find someone part time (5-10k per month) until they raise their series A in March/April.  If the right person willing to join now and make a contribution they would offer a substantial equity stake that could likely amount to something life changing.  If interested send me a resume and lets chat.  I'd love to give you more context on this startup.  Have a great weekend.  Cheers.  Mitchell Corsini Head of Talent

Duration: 6-month contract  Location: (Hybrid Schedule 2 days onsite) Concord, CA Start Date: ASAP Interview Process:  One and Done 1 hour Panel   Must Haves: •	7+ years' experience within Front-End Software development, HTML, JavaScript and jQuery •	1+ years' experience coding in Java.  •	Oracle Database Exposure •	Agile Methodology and CI/CD Pipeline experience   Pluses: •	Background in Banking/Finance Industry •	Experience working on Fraud based applications •	Experience developing Microservices and building RESTful API's       Day to Day:  Insight Global is looking for a seasoned Front-End Software Engineer to join the Fraud and Claims Management team at a financial power house. To be successful in this role, a strong foundation in front-end software development is crucial, more specifically within HTML, JavaScript and jQuery. For this person to make an immediate impact on the team, they must be proficient within Agile practices, continuous integration, and continuous deployment.   Best,  Ethan Hultgren Professional Recruiter at Insight Global

SUBJECT: Remote Full Time Role - Front End/ React Developer @ US bank
CONTENT: Senior React/Responsive Front-End Engineer will be responsible for the analysis, design, testing, development and maintenance of best in class software experiences. The candidate is a self-motivated individual who can collaborate with a team and across the organization. The candidate takes responsibility of the software artifacts produced adhering to U.S Bank standards in order to ensure minimal impact to the customer experience. The candidate will be adept with the agile software development lifecycle and DevOps principles.  Essential Responsibilities:    Responsible for designing, developing, testing, operating and maintaining products using React.js and Angular.  Takes full stack ownership by consistently writing production-ready and testable code.  Consistently creates optimal design adhering to architectural best practices; considers scalability, reliability and performance of systems/contexts affected when defining technical designs.   Makes sound design/coding decisions keeping customer experience in the forefront.   Takes feedback from code review and apply changes to meet standards. Conducts code reviews to provide guidance on engineering best practices and compliance with development procedures.  Accountable for ensuring all aspects of product development follow compliance and security best practices.  Exhibits relentless focus in software reliability engineering standards embedded into development standards.  Embraces emerging technology opportunities and contributes to the best practices in support of the bank’s technology transformation.   Contributes to a culture of innovation, collaboration and continuous improvement  Reviews tasks critically and ensures they are appropriately prioritized and sized for incremental delivery. Anticipates and communicates blockers and delays before they require escalation.

CONTENT: Hi Jason,  I’m reaching out regarding a great opportunity with Undergroundcellar as a Sr UI Engineer, This would be one of the initial members of our UI development team, working closely with the engineering, product, data, and design teams to ensure our product and website are "state of the art" and that we continue to ship exceptional and performant features. This role will report to our Head of Engineering and work cross-functionally with other company leaders to ensure there is a significant input in bringing our product vision to life.  We are on the journey of enriching the customer experience, unlike the other countless "deep discount" ecommerce websites, we take a different approach to helping wineries move inventory.  Rather than providing value to our members through discounts, value is provided through randomized upgrades to more premium wines. Not only does this provide an exciting new way for wine consumers to experience high-end wines they might not otherwise go to the store and buy, but it allows a winery to maintain its price point by never advertising their product at a discount. Discounts ruin brands - We preserve them.  I’d love to get a call scheduled to talk more about the role. Feel free to pop some time on y schedule for an initial call to further discuss the role here: https://calendly.com/fernandor-recruiterpro/30min  Looking forward to hearing from you! Inrupt is seeking a frontend engineer to produce accessible, usable, and efficient applications using our open-source SDKs. Front-End Developer - Brainwahve Qualifying Solutions - Remote  Thanks for making the connection Jason, your interest in this opportunity is very much appreciated.  Brainwahve Qualifying Solutions (BQS) is seeking a senior level Web/Full-Stack Developer with a heavy concentration in Front-End design and development to join the team to play a key role in building their new product suite and supporting Brainwahve’s existing product portfolio. Brainwahve provides SaaS-based contractor, employee, and employer qualification services to ensure accurate placements with maximum satisfaction and minimum turn-over.  Brainwahve Qualifying Solutions is disrupting the biased hiring process for screening and selecting talent. Brainwahve Qualifying Solutions is a unique qualifying hiring process, which enables objectivity in recruiting based on applicant skills and verified experience. BQS provides companies with true blind auditions to increase diversity and decrease turnover.  The successful candidate is a skilled Front-End Web developer who is as at home with CSS, HTML, and front-end frameworks as they are with creating wireframes or building REST services with the latest back-end frameworks. This Senior Front-End/UI/UX/Web/Full-Stack Developer will collaborate closely with other team members and stakeholders on product visuals and workflows to enhance user experiences across multiple platforms.  The Front-End Web developer will be mainly responsible for building the ‘client-side’ of their web applications and should be able to translate the company and customer needs into functional and appealing interactive applications.  Key responsibilities include:  Build and maintain front-ends for Brainwahve’s product portfolio and work with product back-end as needed. Apply marketing brand standards to all user experience elements. Advocate UX/UI design standards, guidelines, and strategies that will serve as the foundation for creating cohesive experiences. These include web pages, applications, navigational elements, portals, templates, etc. Complete regular code and design reviews with the development team. Understand product requirements. Prototype, design and present low-to-high fidelity, eye-catching wireframes and visual designs with engaging compositions that enhance and guide user behavior, eliminate pain points and improve cross-platform user experiences to communicate with stakeholders, developers, and cross-functional teams. Keep abreast of UX trends, other products and industry trends. Research best practices in and around web applications to build features that meet the product vision along with address customer needs. Document project activities and tasks, research and analysis outcomes, and test results.  Relevant Stack: NodeJS TypeScript ReactJS, NestJS Svelte, Smelte, Material, Bootstrap, Tailwind PostgreSQL AWS (EC2, RDS, SQS, Elasticache, Terraform, S3, Route53, etc.)  The candidates we’re seeking have the following experience profile:  - Four-year degree in Computer Science, Web Design, or similar - Located and able to work in the US - 5+ years full-stack application development in a team environment - 3+ years front-end software development in a team environment - Proficient with MS Office Suite Discord, Microsoft Teams, Slack, Zoom, etc. - Understanding of cross-browser compatibility issues, mobile, web, and accessibility standards - Understanding of usability testing and analysis - Familiar with front-end testing tools and frameworks such as: Chai and Chimp etc. - Highly proficient with CSS, HTML, JavaScript, JS frameworks and best practices including but not limited to: Node, Nest, React, Angular, - Svelte, Smelte, MaterialUI, Bootstrap, etc. - Strong team player with first-class spoken and written communication skills working with colleagues and clients at all levels to gather business requirements, present design ideas, receive and incorporate feedback, and explaining ideas and design principals.  The opportunity will provide a solid compensation offering that will match the success and the skills of the candidate. The framework for the compensation plan includes a generous base salary, medical benefits, 401K and stock options.  If you are personally interested in this opportunity and feel you meet the profile, please reply with your resume, which is “for our eyes only.” We will review it and respond back to you as to potential fit.   Alternatively, if you know someone who might be interested and a good match, please feel free to forward this email. Hi Jason, thanks for accepting my request!   I should have given you more context, so the way Wanted works is that as a talent, you just set your salary. Companies will reach out blind via Wanted only based on locations, skills & min. salary. That is when you (as a talent) will know about the company. You will get a page with all the details (committed salary of course but also perks, equity, project, team etc…) Then, only if you accept to reveal your profile, they will know more about you (like who you are). If you don’t like the offer, your profile keeps being anonymous. This way, we keep everyone anonymous until there is a salary+skill match, and the talent accepts the company request. Does it make sense? That is why we will need to know your salary request first (can be something like your current + 15-25%) to check if there is a match etc. Keep in mind that companies working with us pay +30% over the market because we don’t take any placement fees.  Let me know your thoughts, and if you want me to sign you up! (The whole process is free).  Best,  Alaric

CONTENT: Title: Senior Mobile Engineer Location: San Francisco, CA Job Type: Full time / Permanent with our client   Salary: $120-170k Base + (Great benefits, both health and commuter, gym reimbursement, a new office in downtown SF)   Job Description: •	Lead mobile app development and establishing best practices around quality and performance. •	Build enterprise apps used by thousands of grocery managers on the ground floor to manage workflows, drive critical decisions, and gain key insights into their business. •	Providing technical guidance and mentorship to junior developers on the team. •	Collaborate closely with product, design, and our customers to create extraordinary user experiences. •	Work with our ML team to build a full human-in-the-loop system -- one that not only surfaces the most relevant and actionable data to our users, but also continually learns from their input. •	Lay the foundation of our mobile infrastructure to enable continuous app delivery and high stability. •	Scale our mobile app development across iOS and Android to support dozens of partners and brand new product offerings. Job Requirements: •	BS in Computer Science or equivalent experience •	5+ years experience with mobile app development •	Experience leading projects and providing technical direction •	Expert understanding of mobile development and best practices •	Proven track record of shipping high quality apps •	Excellent attention to detail and mobile design sensibilities •	System-level problem solving and excitement to tackle hard problems •	Enjoy working in a fast paced, startup environment •	iOS (Swift) or React Native experience required •	Android experience a big plus  Vijay   Head of Delivery ----------- vj.pandia@two95intl.com

It was the first thing I built at General Assembly.   As far as skilling-up, I've had some experience in the past with mobile automation testing and writing test scripts in Python & Javascript, but I hadn't worked on engineering features in any of my roles at Kixeye & Chartboost.   I've been casually studying engineering for the past few years, but never seemed to build the momentum to have anything to show for it. So after a layoff in October, I decided it was time to go all-in, and attend a software engineering bootcamp. I've been wanting to enroll for years, but it's not possible if you're working a full-time job. So I jumped at the chance.   Having a background in design and some engineering helped, for sure. I storyboarded my apps, and made mockups in Sketch, which I used to build my apps. It was a transformative experience and I'm glad that I went for it.  I don't do game jams now, since I'm trying to get work on the frontend with React, so I've been building React projects in school, and after.   If you'd like to check out my storyboard for Crush It!!!, I have it in my github repo here as a PDF.  https://github.com/JasonToups/CrushIt-BlockCrusherGame/blob/master/design/CrushIt-Storyboard.pdf  If you ever want to connect about anything, feel free to reach out. I don't want to leave the chance of getting a right answer, when I am not 100% sure of the solution. I believe this would be a more fair assessment of my current skills.   Then write up my own skills assessment from the test, noting which areas I believe I did well in, and then detail areas of improvement. Follow that up with action items to work towards developing those skills, including taking a Python course for school to fulfill my Science requirement for my degree. I have to run that past my professor, but considering that I'm focusing on writing my Philosophy papers about the intersection of Philosophy and Software Development, I believe he will approve the coursework. When I'm done with the test, I will submit the test and my written postmortem along with it.   When you get a chance, let me know if or when I can take the assessment.   Also, I attached my Philosophy Term Paper about Agile Methodologies and Adam Smith's Theories of Moral Sentiments, if you are interested in reading about my approach to sympathy in working with a team, and ensuring working code and software. SUBJECT: RE: SDK Testing
CONTENT: Hi Jason ,  Thanks for responding as promised :)  I saw your response and was confused with the calculation :( I confirmed this with our Payroll Manager so I was sure I wasn't missing anything.    She educated me that maybe you're looking at taxes for an Independent contractor, which ARE higher.  As an Independent contractor you do pay higher taxes for yourself and are not entitled to benefits from us. However, when you work with us, you work on W2, as a Consultant employee on our payroll and your taxes remain the same as what you're currently paying.  (Any taxes you pay with us will be dependent on what you declare on your W4)  You can also discuss and confirm this with our CEO when you interview with him.  You are free to withdraw at any point if you think that we are not offering you a good deal, that is you prerogative.  Our aim is to establish a long working relationship and that will happen only if you're happy working with us.   If you're comfortable proceeding with $40/hr W2 with Health insurance and 15 days PTO (equivalent to $80k/year), let me know so we can discuss next steps. There's also the potential of converting to Full time with Oculus and the salary you negotiate will be between you and Oculus .   I know you're occupied with term exams this week, so all you'd need to do is send a confirmation to proceed and you can take the test over the weekend.    PS: My Payroll Manager, Ilisa, is open to talking to you and I can arrange that call if you're still not sure.  Awaiting your response!  Regards, Ruchika

League of Legends is the largest concurrently played game in the world....so we need people like you to keep it up and running for our players!   3.) SUBJECT: Reg: Lead Product Designer position in Redwood City, CA --- Would you be interested?
CONTENT: Hi Jason,   Hope you are doing well.  I have a full time position as Lead Product Designer (UI/UX) and would like to check if you would be interested at this time.  Full time position with excellent benefits and work life culture.  Responsibilities: Reporting to the Director of Product Design, you will work closely with the design team on the UX/UI/VisD of mobile products and desktop software. Lead end-to-end design on major new features and products. Conduct user testing and research, and apply insight to product design. Create user flows, wireframes, color palettes, typography, UI elements, icons and visual polish. Create production-ready pixel perfect graphic assets/comps. Provide UX solutions to complex problems, while maintaining consistent UI guidelines. Present concepts and designs to product managers and team members.  Requirements: Outstanding online portfolio referencing work on mobile and desktop applications. 7+ years experience working as an end-to-end product designer. Experience with 3D software and/or game engines (ie. Maya, Blender, Unity, Unreal). Expertise with UX design principles and processes. A strong eye for usability, typography, layout, and UI design. Expert knowledge of Adobe Creative Cloud, Sketch, and/or Figma. Experience successfully leading production design within interdisciplinary project teams. Strong familiarity with modern Social Networks and Mobile Applications. Excellent organizational, written and verbal communication skills. Self-motivated, proactive, able to multi-task and work independently. Passionate about design, a positive attitude, and creative within an agile development process. Team player eager to solicit feedback and apply team insights on product iteration.   Please let me know if we can discuss the details over the phone sometime this week at your convenience.  Thanks and Regards,   Jyoti Vaidya Lead Technical Recruiter Sohum Inc. (www.sohum.biz) Email: jyoti@sohum.biz Ph: 408-256-8107

Please carefully read the following information:  My email is brian@angularjobs.com. Please send me a message and let me know what you need to grow in your career with React. Or just say "hi" and let me know you're happy to be a part of the group 😄  I'm looking forward to hearing from you.  When I started contributing to the JavaScript Community, React was just an idea. And now it's an important part of the tech stack. And thousands of businesses are using it worldwide!  In this group, we discuss React, and its related technologies, from a perspective that's useful for developers.  Please share blog posts, open-source projects, GitHub issues, Stack Overflow questions, and commentary related to React, React.js, React Native, or derivative technologies.  Let's make this a place where everyone can participate. So please avoid sharing content that is behind a paywall, like for-profit courses and workshops that require buying a ticket.  When in doubt about whether to share something, ask yourself:   "Is this relevant to at least 50% of React Developers?"  For example, job descriptions target a small segment of React Developers based on experience and location. That segment is certainly smaller than 50% of all React Developers. So job descriptions should not be shared in this group.  Employers utilize ReactExpo.com/jobs to reach members of the group about their jobs.   Is your company hiring? Most of my business comes from referrals. And I'd be happy to send you a React t-shirt for showing your support!  Do you want to contribute to the group?   Not sure how?   One way you can help directly is by referring your employer to ReactExpo.com/jobs to post a job.   Are you looking for React courses, jobs, or templates?  Top React Courses for 2020: ReactExpo.com/top-react-courses  Top React Templates for 2020: ReactExpo.com/top-react-templates  One final question:  What do you need to grow in your career with React? https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:activity:6580235624102547457/  Thanks for joining, Brian Petro 386-237-8208 brian@angularjobs.com

The main thing is that in the "induction" phase (as they call it in Atkins) you have to make sure you don't switch out of ketosis by eating (even just a few) carbs. Hey Jessie, sure, happy to!   Toups, good to meet! App Academy is amazing, and certainly put their money where their mouth is (you don't pay them til you get a dev job). I really enjoyed my experience and the people I got to meet. Here's the low down:  Program: A/A does 2 weeks of Ruby, 2 weeks of Rails, 2 weeks of JavaScript, 2 weeks of React, and 2 weeks of final projects, followed by 3 weeks of interview and jobhunt prep. The topics covered are pretty standard for the Rails+JS bootcamps, and their curriculum is constantly updated (it's collaboratively edited by the teachers via Github). Contrast with the other major bootcamp (Hack Reactor), which does a fully-JS stack. The difference is basically whether you want to work in JS or Ruby.  Admittance: They get a lot of applicants, but not all of them are good. The admittance rate is low (5%), consequently. They are looking for students they can count on to place, because they don't get paid if you don't! This means that the students that end up at a/A typically have some background in tech or development. They come from all over - we had a nuclear physics PhD, a cohort of UCLA students, and 2 high-school dropouts.  Admittance - Interviewing: There's a first round phone screen, which you should be prepared for if you've covered the fundamentals of programming (loops, conditionals, and variables). Then you'll have a coding challenge or another phone screen, and then you'll hear if you're accepted! This is followed by some prework (~10 hrs or so).  Post-graduation: there are 3 weeks of interview and jobhunt prep. This involves the lead instructor teaching you about common interview problems, algorithms, and data structures. The job hunt process is very structured - they have an idea of what your resume, cover letter, and GitHub should look like, and they have stats on how their process works. Basically your goal is to send out 200 applications, and (as of my cohort) for every 20 apps you send you get a phone screen, for every 2 phone screens you do you get an onsite, for every 2 onsites you do you get an offer. 200 apps roughly translates to 2-3 offers. Then they help you negotiate between them and get the highest offer you can. I think average starting salary in SF is $105k.   Some notes on applying to bootcamps (my personal opinion):  You should choose App Academy over DBC or Hack Reactor because of the job guarantee. As far as bootcamps go, in quality of curriculum and who I see getting placed in jobs, I see the rankings as: 1) Hack Reactor and App Academy; 2) Galvanize; 3) Dev Bootcamp/MakerSquare/whoever else has popped up recently, with Hackbright an outlier (women only). I'd recommend applying to at least Hack Reactor, App Academy, and Galvanize if you are serious about transitioning to development, and I'd be happy to refer you. That said, YMMV, and you should definitely meet people from each school and see how you like the vibe you get from them. You have experience in the tech industry so you should be able to tell what you are looking for.  Hope helpful and let me know if I can clarify anything,  Frank

SUBJECT: Contract position: Sr Software Developer-work location: downtown San Francisco-hybrid
CONTENT: Hi Jason  Please contact me if you would like to hear more:   Duration: 6 mos. to start/with anticipated extension(s) Location: downtown SF-hybrid-3 days onsite/2 days remote  Seeking a Sr Software Developer to implement a UI. Primarily a frontend development role with some backend API dev & DevOps/automation.   Duties:  -Exp. with React, real-time data synchronization, web application & backend Rest API dev. -Redesign an existing portal. UI wireframes are already completed, looking for a developer who can implement the UI.  -Frontend dev is the core, but this person should know the backend API integration.  React, HTML, CSS, knowledge of Jenkins for CI/CD is a must. NLP, ML & OpenShift design is a plus. -Participate in medium-to large-scale, complex, cross-functional projects by reviewing project requirements & translating them into technical solutions -Develop a modular & flexible library of components for reuse & rich UI. -Adopt best practices in HTML & CSS to improve reliability, performance & accessibility -Use Responsive Web Design techniques in web development by reviewing mockups, animating them on the desktop & mobile devices -Collaborate with backend developers, translate UI designs into structured & well-organized HTML/CSS, compatible with modern browsers. Familiarity with CI/CD, unit testing & automated frontend testing  Exp./Skills:  -At least 6yrs. of frontend focused web dev, optimization problem solving, complexity analysis, OOD, UI & functional programming. Strong with React, HTML & CSS & Python -Exp. working with mobile solutions, web applications, real-time data synchronization, Rest API development and an understanding of DevOps/Automation. Exp. with cross-browser compatibility -Implementing best practices, design patterns such as application flow control, event/error handling -Data collection & analytics -Agile & Scrum dev methodologies  Ted Lambert Sr. Account Mgr. GoAhead Solutions LLC. ted@goaheadsolutions.com 650-873-7253

Jason

Hi Jason, that's great your building a portfolio!  Personally I would taylor it to the product design sign, you'll want to highlight for each project: Intro (problem, solution, thought process) Wire frames (sketches on paper is fine) Visual exploration , if any (optional) Final mocks Takeaways Key takeaways  I believe  design recruiters are looking not only for the imagery/visual elements; but mostly and mainly for the thought process you put into it. In essence, write! Each element on the portfolio should be a case study. The person reading it should see what problem you tried to solve via design, how you solved it (via design) and what he results were (cold hard numbers or if not available just key takeaways)  Look at this website (my wife's) www.carolapc.com The structure she has is good and got her interviews with FB, Uber, yelp and task rabbit within one week.  Hope this helps!

SUBJECT: Jason, quick question...
CONTENT: Hi Jason,    I hope this message finds you well! Your LinkedIn profile caught my attention as you mentioned you have done mobile automation with JavaScript. Would you be open to a brief chat sometime this week? Ideally, I'd like to discuss a QA Engineering position with a mobile gaming company, Playstudios.    Have you ever heard of Playstudios? If not, they’re the gaming studio behind one of the most popular casino apps in the world – MyVegas.    Founded by a team of casino and gaming industry veterans, Playstudios distinguished itself early by developing an unprecedented player loyalty program offering real-world rewards. Points are earned based on frequency and length of play, as well as participation in social actions, then redeemed for prizes ranging from free drinks to a chance to appear as a guest DJ in a hugely popular night club. (Yes, as in YOU, Jason Toups, are the on-stage DJ)    Today, MyVegas remains a massive success with over 1M daily active users and more than 18M downloads. Playstudios just closed a $20M round of funding, and is prepared to invest aggressively in furthering the already successful brand they've created, possibly on an international level.    The position offers highly competitive compensation, solid equity, unlimited PTO, and unparalleled health/dental benefits. (100% coverage for not only you, but any dependents as well)     If that sounds like something you'd be interested in being a part of, please feel free to suggest a time for us to chat this week. I'll make myself available at your earliest convenience, off-work hours are fine too.    Thank you in advance and have a wonderful week.    Pierce

Hi Jason, we have developed the world's first Interactive Video Pro Hockey Card Game [also concepts for Soccer, Basketball, Golf] and I'm looking to open a dialogue with Pro Players, Agents and Team Owners for Endorsement/Investment and also to align with Professionals with regard to Production, Advertising, Marketing, Development, Investment and Sponsors/NHL-Licensed Corporations.  I believe a fresh New Casual game concept like this could easily rival the 'Poker.com' enterprises and you could also sell the Game online as well as having Live Tournament Play without the 'gambling' aspect.  This could also be a great Corporate PR asset; akin to how Microsoft offers their customers free online interactive computer games.  Who knows; if marketed properly, you could be looking at the Next Most Popular Casual Game Concept?     You're welcomed to play my NHL Card Hockey Demo from here: http://www.tegarttech.com/cardhockey/cardhockey_setup_B2.10_NHL08.exe for Windows only.  Enjoy and rest assured, the Game’s Programmer designed this Demo and set up the site so it is a Safe download.  You can also view Brian's profile on LinkedIn.     Target Market: i.e. Estimating there are at least 15 million Hockey fans in Canada and the US and charging only $10 per game; then with just 1% return, gross sales would be $1.5 million and that is a very low estimate.  Realistically, there are probably way more than 25 million Hockey fans in N. America alone and even the weakest marketing job should perhaps garner more than 1% return?  This is also convertible to a Soccer(Football) version and the World Football market is probably 50 to 100 times bigger than Hockey, perhaps more.  So the Numbers are there and the real potential for this Game is staggering once you factor in all the Card players and casual PC gamers in the world too.    I have an NHL Player to endorse the game and also welcome negotiation with Pro Soccer Players with regard to endorsement opportunities for the Football\Soccer version but would prefer a Player(s) investment and endorsement role.  For the Soccer version, you simply reduce the Scoring frequency, swap the Hockey Arena background for a Football Pitch, use Pro Football Player's names, Team Logos, make it Two Halves instead of 3 Periods, add features like Crowd Noise and everything else like that.  But the game-play is essentially the same and when a Goal is scored, instead of using the Horn audio effect, you could have a Voiceover that shouts the word: Gooooooooooooooal! or something equivalent.    Investment is all this venture needs because there is not that much development left to be done to the Game that is complicated or time consuming for a Professional Developer and so ideally I would prefer an Investor with sufficient resources to take over the project through to completing development, licensing if necessary and marketing the Game.  Which means the Investor/Partner will be expected to absorb those costs because we have done as much as are capable and can afford.  Of course, I will also assist with development if I may to share all the other design features for the game.  Let me know if there is anything else you need and I can also put anyone in touch with the game's Programmer for all "technical" queries.  Thanks for your consideration and look forward to discussing if you're interested or perhaps can refer me to someone else.  Naturally you would be compensated from proceeds should any of your referrals lead to a successful outcome.  Kind regards.    Paul Fletcher (Owner)   Email: card-hockey@shaw.ca   1-403-288-9502  Calgary, Canada  http://www.tegarttech.com/cardhockey

SUBJECT: Freelancer - Opportunity with FloCareer (Side Job) - Senior Frontend End React
CONTENT: Hi ,  Ashi here from FloCareer, I hope you're doing well.  We found your profile suits our current requirements. and here are more details about our company.  So I'd like to introduce FloCareer to you! :) https://www.flocareer.com/ We have a rich pool of 4000+ SMEs (Subject Matter Experts), who take remote tech video interviews on behalf of our clients.  The Senior Developers who work with us as technical interviewers do it in their free time, in flexible slots of their choice, mostly as a side job.  You will get free training on your interviewing and communication skills, mingle with like-minded freelancers across the globe, and know the latest updates on technology and trends. Be your own boss and earn extra money in your free time!  Compensation:  We will pay you for each interview you conduct.  Privacy: Your identity is never revealed, neither to the candidate nor the client, and the interviewer's video isn't shown to the hiring companies.  Based on your availability, interviews will be scheduled on our platform and an easy way to provide detailed feedback about the candidate on our platform.   As our clients are tech companies mostly from the USA, the interviews follow the USA time zones (EST, PST, etc.) - also UK time zones sometimes - and our working hours easily fit into free time slots.  Each conducted interview length is around 45/50 minutes and the compensation is $30 per interview (monthly paid through the platform Payoneer).  Share your updated resume and reach out to the below email, or contact number and let us know a good time to discuss more about this Opportunity.  Ashi Johri Senior Quality Manager @ FloCareer | ISO-9001 Certified | Quality Assurance | Process Excellence | Lean Six Sigma Green belt | Ex HCL, EXL, Lenskart, Paytm
